I think the implementation plan for the Res and Small Commercial makes good=
=20
sense.  This is good intelligence for preparing our curves and pricing=20
models; however, these customers are not our commercial focus and only tend=
=20
to show up as a few sites in a portfolio of sites.  SDG&E's plan was our=20
preferred plan to the extent that the Legislature or Commission had=20
implemented a mandatory rate cap for all size customers.

With respect to the larger opt-in customers, I expect that this is only=20
available to Standard Offer customers.  SDG&E should prevent cost shifting =
to=20
other customers who do not benefit from the cap, i.e. SO customers who do n=
ot=20
opt-in and DA customers who do not have the option.  Even customers who=20
opt-in will vary by differing degrees in terms of the size of the customer=
=20
and timeframe.  It seems to me, the only equitable implementation plan for=
=20
the opt-in customers is a customer-specific balancing account, similar to=
=20
that which is implemented for the balanced payment plan; otherwise too much=
=20
gaming will ensue which would result in the need for administratively=20
burdensome tracking.  To the extent that SDG&E makes all customers, includi=
ng=20
DA customers, pay for the undercollections, we can switch our customers to=
=20
Standard Offer without any negative ramifications.  (Note: It would be=20
difficult to exercise such a "regulatory switching option" if only those=20
customers who benefit incur a surcharge into the future, because our=20
customers would balk at us exercising the option during our contract term a=
nd=20
imposing a future liability on our customer beyond the contract term.)  In=
=20
fact, it might be better if all customers were expected to pay for the=20
undercollections so that we can exercise the regulatory switching option. =
=20
What do others think?  I think we can work with either implementation=20
method.  If it is a customer-specific balancing account, we will make=20
customers know that the lower rates is the equivalent to a loan they will=
=20
need to eventually pay off.  If it is all customers who are expected to pay=
,=20
we will exercise the regulatory switching option.  We need to be careful no=
t=20
to share too much of this strategy and insights with the utility, because=
=20
they will counter by imposing new rules and charges for switching customers=
=20
between DA and SO.

I don't believe that SDG&E's shareholders should be held accountable for a=
=20
percentage of the shortfalls.  This would provide a subsidy to SO service. =
 I=20
believe it is more important that customers realize that the utility's SO=
=20
service is not the right solution versus trying to drive the utility away=
=20
from SO service.  Either outcome works for us.

The last issue I will address is the timing of recovery of the=20
undercollections.  Will recovery begin during the period of the cap such th=
at=20
the cap will effectively be implemented as a freeze?  Or will the recovery=
=20
begin after the cap expires, resulting in otherwise higher future rates. =
=20
Defering cost recovery will always work to our advantage from a book=20
perspective.  The key for me is to know asap the details, so that we can=20
properly model our curves for pricing new deals and reflect the changes in=
=20
our book.  However, since these questions largely pertain to the smaller=20
customers in SDG&E's service territory, I do not anticipate a large impact =
on=20
our book and our marketing efforts.  In fact, I think the burdens of the=20
modeling changes would outweigh much of the benefits of this legislation fo=
r=20
us.

Thanks for the intelligence.

Roger=20

