Governor has NOT signed AB 1156, $150 million from the general fund.  He HA=
S=20
signed AB 265 (SDG&E rate cap bill) and AB 970 (expedited siting for=20
non-permanent peaking).

I had a conversation today with Wayne Sakarias from SDG&E about=20
implementation.   It appears, based on the press release, that the Commissi=
on=20
will act tomorrow to adopt an order that will begin the implementation=20
process, although the order is not available for review yet.

I asked Wayne how they intended to implement the bill.  He believes that th=
e=20
opt-in provision for large C&I customers, and any associated undercollectio=
ns=20
associated with the customers that opt-in, would be handled separately from=
=20
the general application of the rate cap for residential and small commercia=
l=20
customers.  I asked how they would collect any shortfalls.   It didn't soun=
d=20
like they had a plan yet.  I suggested balancing account treatment for the=
=20
customers that benefit from the opt-in with any shortfalls recovered as=20
quickly as possible but no later than 1 year. =20

Relative to Res/Small Commercial:

He said that SDG&E will propose, in response to ARM comments, that the cap=
=20
(for res and small commercial) customers would not disadvantage DA=20
customers.  In other words, they are concerned about the appearances that=
=20
SDG&E's rates would be lower than market prices because of the cap and woul=
d=20
make available to DA customers a comparable pricing mechanism, that in=20
effect, would eliminate any pricing advantage by staying w/ SDG&E. =20

For example:  If prevailing market prices were 7.5 cents/kWh, SDG&E's res a=
nd=20
small commercial customers would only be charged upto 6.5 cents, and DA=20
customers would receive a 1 cent/kWh credit against their T&D charges so th=
at=20
in effect, there is no economic advantage to staying w/ SDG&E.  However, wh=
en=20
it comes time to pay the piper for undercollections, DA and bundled custome=
rs=20
would again be treated comparably.

Their BIG concern is that the Commission will hang them out to dry on=20
reasonableness. =20

We agreed to keep the dialogue open.  Things will likely happen quickly.  I=
f=20
folks have any recommendations or see problems with the above, let me know=
=20
asap.  Thanks.

Mona


